post_text:
We would like to express our appreciation for the success of the alternative meal program during the COVID-19 crisis to the following groups:

Our generous donators,

·Rose Acres for donating 300 dozen eggs, which allowed us to distribute a dozen eggs to each family for 3 weeks.

·Aldi Foods for donating grocery bags, which allowed for each child to have their own sack on distribution days.

·Ruler Foods for donating loaves of bread to include with the meals.

·Healthy Communities for the many household items that were passed out to the families.

We would also like to thank the parents who signed up their children and picked up their meals. We would like to thank Mr. Remaly for all his help and support in the planning and all the hours he spent helping with our distribution of the meals. We would like to thank our Administration for helping pass out the meals. We also acknowledge our fellow co-workers who worked hard together and with combined efforts in the Elementary to prepare and pass out the meals.

Sincerely,
Becky McQuinn and Tina Crum

Brandon received a gas forge so he can heat metal to reshape it into something new. The forge can get up to 2,300° Fahrenheit. He is in the process of turning a railroad spike into something new! He took interest in blacksmithing while visiting the state fair a few years ago.

What a unique skill to learn and some special time with his dad!

Brandon will be a 5th grader at CCE this fall.

Rory has been working hard preparing and planting her family's garden this spring. She learned how to read the back of the seed packet to see how long they take to reach maturity. She’s began by growing the seeds, then transplanted them into the garden.

Being responsible for planting and growing a garden takes lots of patience, commitment, and hard work. Great job Rory!

Rory will be a fifth grader at CCE this fall.

post_text:
Does your student help with the garden, or have projects they work on? Do they enjoy science or STEM activities? Whether it's academic activities, or life skills, we would like to highlight ways that students are continuing to learn, outside the classroom, over the summer.

In order for your student's activity to be highlighted, please send a short description and a photo through a private message here on the elementary Facebook page. We do ask that you send no more than one per week of each individual student so that we may highlight as many students as possible. These learning experiences can involve just the student(s) or the entire family learning together. Please do not post these photos and stories in the comments.

We can't wait to see how our Bulldogs are learning over the summer!

Clinton Central Jr Sr High School
April 22 at 4:12 PM ·

Important update for student-athletes and parents:
Completed physical packets that were in use for the 2019-20 school year (for grades 5-11) will be permitted - by the IHSAA and the Committee on Sports Medicine at the Indiana State Medical Association - for use during the 2020-21 school year, ONLY if a physical packet is currently on file in the Athletic Office. We do ask that the Athletic Office be contacted if any information needs to be updated (personal or medical). Updated physical packets for the 2020-21 school year will soon be available in the Athletic Office and on the school website.

shared_text:
Clinton County Daily News added 85 new photos to the album: 4-4-20 Clinton Central Teachers Parade by Patty Keaton Parks.
April 4 at 1:23 PM ·

Clinton Central teachers in 40 cars spent the morning parading through Michigantown, Forest, Scircleville, Hillisburg, and Kirklin along with Michigantown and Kirklin Fire Departments to help out to say goodbye to their students for the year due to the Coronavirus outbreak. This was done in a safe manner with parents and children in or in front of their vehicles or from the safety of their own home at front door or on porches waving to their favorite teachers. There was no social gathering what so ever done with each staying their distance.

post_text:
Details on tomorrow’s staff parade. Thank you to our local fire departments for your help with this event!

Fire Departments will be leading us through the towns, so when you hear the sirens the CC staff have arrived in your town.

Our route will be 29 to Michigantown around the streets of Michigantown
29 to 600 N to Forest around the town
Out 930E to 100 N to 1100 Scircleville around town
Out 28 to 900 to Hillisburg around town
Back to 100N through school parking lot
Down 29 to Kirklin around town
End of Parade:)

We will leave by 10:10 to start parade!

post_text:
The Governor announced today that schools will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. If you have been following the news, this should not come as a big surprise but it is definitely the right thing to do.

Our new normal of e learning will continue under the current format for the remainder of the year. Clinton Central will also continue to use the waiver days allowed and in the next couple of days, we will be sending out a calendar for the remainder of the year. We know there will be questions about graduation, credits, being promoted to the next grade, etc… Once the administration knows all of the specifics, we will communicate them to you.

We greatly appreciate all your efforts at home, remember we are all in this together.

post_text:
Clinton Central Families,

Our teachers have been working hard to prepare enhanced eLearning lessons for all grade levels. Please be sure to check email tomorrow for instructions from your teachers. Keep in mind that students will receive instruction from multiple teachers within their grade level, as teachers are sharing the workload of preparing lessons. It is important to keep in communication with your student's teacher through e-mail with any questions specific to eLearning. In addition to their regular classroom lessons, your child will have lessons from specials teachers.

The office staff will be available to take calls from 9:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. tomorrow, Monday, March 30.

Thank you for your patience as we all work through this new way of teaching/learning together!

Good Morning Bulldog Families,

We are pleased to announce that our awesome cafeteria staff will once again be putting together Breakfast and Lunches for our Clinton Central students and siblings (Infant - 12th grade).

Pick up will be Monday, March 30th and Wednesday, April 1st from 4:30pm - 6pm, in the Elementary Cafeteria. (Located on the Northside of the Elementary - doors N7 & N8)

You MUST PRE-ORDER by NOON March 30th for both pickups!!!! (Even if you only want April 1st meals)
Monday's pick up will contain 2 days of food - Wednesday's pick up will contain 3 days of food

Call Becky McQuinn - 765-249-0202 or email - becky.mcquinn@clinton.k12.in.us
or Tina Crum - 765-249-2244 ext 3376 or email - tina.crum@clinton.k12.in.us

School Supplies are available too for pick up during this time!

We hope you are all staying safe and we wish you all good health.

Clinton Central School Corporation

post_text:
CCE Families,

As you all have most likely heard by now, Clinton Central will be closed until May 1st. As a result, some changes have been made to our eLearning days. Beginning March 30th, eLearning will only take place on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays through the first of May. State standardized testing has been canceled for the remainder of the school year.

As a reminder, please e-mail your classroom teacher with questions specific to your eLearning assignments.

The staff at CCE thank you for your patience and understanding during this time. We hope you all enjoy time with your family over spring break.

Clinton Central Food Services will be providing free food to Clinton Central students, as well as any child in the district, ages infant through 18 years old. This includes breakfast and lunch meals.

Food will be distributed today, Wednesday, March 18th from 4:30 pm to 6:00pm and it will need to be PICKED UP at Door N7 or N8 at Clinton Central Elementary.

Food must be pre-ordered by calling or emailing no later than Wednesday, March 18th at 12 noon.

You may call at 249-0202 or email becky.mcquinn@clinton.k12.in.us

In addition to food pick up, we have a limited amount of school supplies available that your student may need to complete e-learning assignments. A table will be set up for these supplies to be picked up in the cafeteria during the food distribution times.

Food will be distributed today, Wednesday, March 18th from 4:30 pm to 6:00pm and it will need to be PICKED UP at Door N7 or N8 at Clinton Central Elementary.

Food must be pre-ordered by calling or emailing no later than Wednesday, March 18th at 12 noon.

You may call at 249-0202 or email becky.mcquinn@clinton.k12.in.us

In addition to food pick up, we have a limited amount of school supplies available that your student may need to complete e-learning assignments. A table will be set up for these supplies to be picked up in the cafeteria during the food distribution times.

post_text:
The Central CyberDAWGS elementary robotics teams, 13301A and 13301C competed at the largest state robotics competition in the country today!
.
Team 13301A finished 26th out of 201 teams in skills. They had tough competition in the alliance matches, but have worked so hard all year. They hope to be invited to Worlds with their skills score. They are currently ranked 176th in the WORLD out of 5,524 elementary teams.
.
Team 13301C finished 61st out of 201 teams in skills. They placed 18th in their division (67 total teams) advancing to finals. The top five alliances advance to Worlds. They finished 6th due to an error, but are hoping for an invitation to Worlds.
.
Congratulations to both teams and thank you to Bryce & Emily Eaton for coaching the teams!

If your child is sent home by the nurse, they may not return the following day, as the 24-hour time period has not passed. If a child that has been sent home returns the following day, you will be called to pick them up.
Please help us prevent the spread of these illnesses.

Clinton Central Elementary is partnering with Traders Point Church to collect caps for a green bench from Green Tree Plastics. This bench is 100% recycled and made from all sorts of plastic caps. Student Council is heading up this project by advertising, sorting, weighing, and packing the plastic caps that are brought in. Below are some details!

- We need 200 pounds of plastic caps and lids for a Green bench
- Bring in your caps to the bucket in your grade level hallway
- Accepting caps and lids from plastic bottles, applesauce pouches, butter/sour cream tubs, coffee cans, condiment bottles, detergent bottles, milk jugs, etc.
- NOT accepting caps and lids from pump or spray bottles, fast food drink lids, medical supplies, anything with metal

post_text:
Dear Families...
With winter break coming to an end, we are encouraging everyone to give their children's coats, hats, gloves, backpacks, and lunch bags a good wash before they return to school on Monday, January 6th. Help everyone stay healthy this winter by not spreading germs!

Also, The cold weather and snow has returned! Please make sure your children are dressed appropriately for these days. Hats, boots, scarves, warm winter jackets, and gloves are essential for students to enjoy their time at recess outside, and stay safe to and from school each day. If the “feels like” temperature is 20 degrees or above, students will go outside for recess. If your child is in need of any of these items, please contact the school for assistance.

We hope you have all had a great break and are looking forward to seeing all of our Bulldogs back on Monday!
